english:
  title: On Governance
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: "The King speaks thus: The art of governing a realm must have its foundation and its superstructure, and the order of practicing this way must likewise have its beginning and its end. Can we speak in detail of the foundation and superstructure, the beginning and end of the governance in the age of Tang, Yu, and the Three Dynasties? Confucius said: \"The Yin inherited the rites of the Xia, and thus we know what they preserved and what they reformed. The Zhou inherited the rites of the Yin, and thus we know what they preserved and what they reformed.\" Yet if the sage-kings Yu, Tang, Wen, and Wu were so illustrious, why did each reform differently from the last? In the ages after the Three Dynasties, those whom we call great administrators are but the Han, Tang, and Song—can we likewise speak of the foundation and superstructure, the beginning and end of their governance? The Han succeeded the Qin, the Tang succeeded the Sui, the Song succeeded the Zhou of Chai—did they not also merely preserve and reform in turn? \n\nOur realm inherited the twilight chaos of the former dynasty. My late father, the Grand Progenitor, rescued our people from the depths of suffering, established this dynasty, and passed down its line. I, unworthy though I am, continue his work with utmost care, sleepless in my vigilance, striving ever toward peace. Yet the hearts and customs of the people still cling to the old ways of the former reign. How can we govern well without making necessary reforms? \n\nHow then shall we bring harmony to heaven and earth, that wind and rain come in their seasons, and the court stands righteous while customs flourish? How shall we apportion taxes justly, that the people's wealth suffices, military discipline strengthens, and soldiers grow keen? How shall we diminish litigation, that wrongs be righted and the innocent find relief? How shall we give the people fixed homes so they do not wander, and provide for all needs without burdening them further with taxes? Can we not recapture, even in the smallest measure, the governance of the Three Dynasties and beyond? You have all studied these matters deeply and surely know these answers well. Speak them plainly, without concealment."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tang and Yu refer to legendary sage-kings of antiquity; the Three Dynasties are the Xia, Shang (Yin), and Zhou.
  - key: ''
    value: The "foundation and superstructure" (본말) refer to the root principles and their practical applications in governance.
  - key: ''
    value: '"Preserve and reform" (손익) reflects the Confucian principle that each dynasty, while maintaining core virtues, adapts institutions to new circumstances.'
  - key: ''
    value: This piece appears to be an examination question or policy prompt, likely addressed to Confucian scholars serving at court.
